        <h1><i class="fas fa-shield-alt"></i> Quantum Mechanics in the Temporal Framework</h1>
        <p>
            Quantum mechanics, when viewed through the lens of the Unified Universe Theory, reveals new insights into phenomena like quantum tunneling. The probability of quantum tunneling is modified to include the effect of observation energy, which is crucial in understanding how particles behave under observation.
        </p>
        <h2>3.1 Quantum Tunneling Probability</h2>
        <p>
            The probability of quantum tunneling, including the effect of observation energy, is given by:
        </p>
        <div class="math-equation">
            <span>P(tunnel) = exp(-2d√(2m(V-E)) / ℏ) * (1 - exp(-E_obs / (k * ℏ * c)))</span>
        </div>
        <p>
            Where:
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>d</strong> is the barrier width.</li>
            <li><strong>m</strong> is the particle mass.</li>
            <li><strong>V</strong> is the potential barrier height.</li>
            <li><strong>E</strong> is the particle energy.</li>
            <li><strong>E_obs</strong> is the energy imparted by observation.</li>
            <li><strong>k</strong> is a constant (to be determined).</li>
            <li><strong>ℏ</strong> is the reduced Planck constant.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
            The presence of observation energy <strong>E_obs</strong> modifies the traditional quantum tunneling probability by adding a factor that accounts for the interaction of energy with the particle. This interaction can increase the particle's ability to cross barriers by momentarily altering its energy state.
        </p>
        <p>
            <strong>Example:</strong> For an electron tunneling through a 1 nm barrier with <strong>V = 10 eV</strong>, <strong>E = 5 eV</strong>, and <strong>E_obs = 1 eV</strong>:
        </p>
        <div class="math-equation">
            <span>P(tunnel) ≈ 0.004 * (1 - exp(-1.6 x 10^-19 / (1.05 x 10^-34 * 3 x 10^8)))</span>
        </div>
        <div class="math-equation">
            <span>P(tunnel) ≈ 0.00398</span>
        </div>
        <p>
            This calculation gives a small but non-zero tunneling probability, consistent with quantum mechanical expectations. The inclusion of observation energy highlights the role of external interactions in influencing quantum events.
        </p>

        <!-- Simplified Explanation -->
        <h2><i class="fas fa-lightbulb"></i> Simplified Explanation</h2>
        <p>
            Imagine a particle trying to cross a hill that it normally wouldn't have enough energy to climb. When we observe the particle, we give it a little extra push, helping it cross the hill by taking a "shortcut" through time. The more energy we use to observe it, the higher the chance it has to cross the hill. This is what quantum tunneling looks like when we consider the energy from observation.
        </p>

